This paper describes a new hardware-friendly readout stage for the liquid state machine, a popular model for reservoir computing. The paper focuses on the implementation of this readout stage in low power neuromorphic VLSI, which suggests that it is likely to fall under the categories of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.ET (Emerging Technologies). The paper also discusses the use of address event representation (AER) protocols commonly used in current neuromorphic systems, which suggests that it could also fall under the category of cs.AR (Hardware Architecture). The paper involves the use of learning algorithms and network rewiring, which suggests that it could also fall under the categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.SY (Systems and Control).
